UID:c51407462c25b89b@sos-elections.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202233Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260625
SUMMARY:[Maine Secretary of State] Secretary of State Shenna Bellows state
 ment on Postmaster General’s declaration USPS will refuse to deliver ele
 ction mail
DESCRIPTION:AUGUSTA\, MAINE\n–Secretary of State Shenna Bellows issued t
 he following statement in response to Postmaster General David Steiner dec
 laration to lawmakers Wednesday that the U.S. Postal Service will decline 
 to deliver mail-in ballots in states that refuse to provide sensitive vote
 r data to the federal government\, despite numerous court decisions ruling
  in the states’ favor. Today\,\nU.S. District Judge Indira Talwani\nrule
 d that the federal government cannot decide who can vote by mail.\n“Neve
 r in the history of the United States has the U.S. Postal Service declined
  to mail ballots for political reasons. In Maine\, many voters including s
 eniors\, people with disabilities and Mainers working multiple jobs rely o
 n the mail to get and return absentee ballots\,” said Secretary Bellows.
  “The idea that the U.S. Postal Service would refuse to deliver any ball
 ots in a state where we have properly refused the Trump Administration’s
  demands for voter data is an illegal and unconstitutional attempt to keep
  Americans from voting. We’ve won every court case on this issue\, and w
 e’re not going to back down now in defending Mainers’ voting rights.
 ”\nAccording to federal law: “The Postal Service shall have as its b
 asic function the obligation to provide postal services to bind the Nati
 on together through the personal\, educational\, literary\, and business c
 orrespondence of the people. It shall provide prompt\, reliable\, and effi
 cient services to patrons in all areas and shall render postal services 
 to all communities.”\n30 states have declined to share state voter lists
  with the federal government. The states have won nine lawsuits where the 
 Department of Justice has sued to compel the states to hand over the voter
  lists. The DOJ has not won any of the voter data lawsuits\, although they
  have appealed the rulings to higher courts.\nEarlier this week\, federal 
 courts struck down key provisions of both of the Trump Executive Orders pe
 rtaining to elections including the Executive Order that directed t\nhttps
 ://www.maine.gov/sos/news/secretary-state-shenna-bellows-statement-postmas
 ter-generals-declaration-usps-will-refuse
URL:https://www.maine.gov/sos/news/secretary-state-shenna-bellows-statemen
 t-postmaster-generals-declaration-usps-will-refuse
CATEGORIES:Maine Secretary of State
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:a62cbfd2f390fdc7@sos-elections.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202233Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260625
SUMMARY:[Maine Secretary of State] Maine Secretary of State’s Office ann
 ounces results of House District 49 recount
DESCRIPTION:AUGUSTA\, MAINE\n– The Department of the Secretary of State 
 announced the results for a recount for House District 49 – Republican (
 Arrowsic\, Georgetown\, Phippsburg\, West Bath\, Woolwich):\n√\nSuzanne 
 Andresen – 608\nNicolas Hamlin – 602\nNicolas Hamlin of West Bath requ
 ested a recount after Suzanne Andresen of West Bath was declared the winne
 r with an 8-vote (609-601) margin. District 49 is currently represented by
  Representative Allison Hepler (D-Woolwich).\nHouse District 135 Democrat 
 is also scheduled for a recount today. Recounts are open to the public and
  media and are livestreamed on the Secretary of State’s\nYouTube page\n.
 \nRecount process:\nMaine statute\nTitle 21-A\, §737-A\nlays out a specif
 ic plan\, process and any related costs for votes to be recounted. In a re
 count\, representatives of each candidate and staff members from the Depar
 tment of the Secretary of State manually review each paper ballot to deter
 mine the official vote tally:\nIn non-Ranked Choice races:\nany candidate 
 other than the apparent winner who desires a recount must file with the Se
 cretary of State a written request for a recount within five business days
  after the election.\nIn Ranked Choice Voting races\n: only a candidate wh
 o received one of the top three rankings at the end of the penultimate rou
 nd of ranked‑choice counting may request a recount\, and they must file 
 with the Secretary of State a written request within five business days af
 ter results are announced.\nOfficial results must be presented to the gove
 rnor within 20 days of the election (Monday\, June 29) and will be posted 
 on the\nElection Results page\n.\n###\nhttps://www.maine.gov/sos/news/main
 e-secretary-states-office-announces-results-house-district-49-recount
URL:https://www.maine.gov/sos/news/maine-secretary-states-office-announces
 -results-house-district-49-recount
CATEGORIES:Maine Secretary of State
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:418e0e7e64df2962@sos-elections.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202233Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260624
SUMMARY:[Maine Secretary of State] Secretary of State Shenna Bellows state
 ment on federal court striking down provisions of anti-voting Executive Or
 der
DESCRIPTION:AUGUSTA\, MAINE\n– Secretary of State Shenna Bellows issued
  the following statement in response to Chief U.S. District Judge Denise C
 asper permanently enjoining provisions of a 2025 anti-voting Executive Ord
 er by President Trump.\n“Donald Trump continues to stack up loss after l
 oss in court\, and as we are now just days away from the 250\nth\nannivers
 ary of the birth of our nation\, states continue to show that when we stan
 d united\, we can successfully defend the rule of law and our rights to ad
 minister elections.\nThe judge could not have stated it more plainly – t
 he U.S. Constitution assigns control over elections to the States and does
  not grant the president any powers over elections. We will continue to fi
 ght Donald Trump and the DOJ’s every attempt to interfere with free and 
 fair elections.”\nThe ruling comes in response to a 19-state litigation 
 challenging the order and stated\, “there is no evidence in this record 
 of widespread “illegal voting\, discrimination\, fraud\, and other forms
  of malfeasance and error” within American elections\, which the Executi
 ve Order purports to safeguard against.”\n###\nAttachment:\nMemorandum a
 nd Order\nhttps://www.maine.gov/sos/news/secretary-state-shenna-bellows-st
 atement-federal-court-striking-down-provisions-anti-voting
URL:https://www.maine.gov/sos/news/secretary-state-shenna-bellows-statemen
 t-federal-court-striking-down-provisions-anti-voting
CATEGORIES:Maine Secretary of State
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
