UID:a2c4ffb576989488@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260716T033355Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Maine Commercial Fishing Remembrance
  Day - July 21
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, the State of Maine has long been shaped by the pro
 ud and enduring traditions of our working waterfronts\, where generations 
 have built their lives and livelihoods on the sea\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, comme
 rcial fishing remains one of Maine’s most iconic and economically vital 
 industries\, supporting thousands of hardworking men and women and contrib
 uting significantly to coastal communities and the state’s heritage\, ec
 onomy\, and way of life\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, the risks faced by Maine’s fi
 shermen are real and constant\, with unpredictable weather\, treacherous w
 aters\, and the physical demands of the job posing dangers each day they s
 et out to sea\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, too many have made the ultimate sacrifice
  in the pursuit of their work\, and Maine communities continue to bear the
  deep and lasting sorrow of lives lost to the sea\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, July 
 21\, 2026 shall serve as a solemn day of remembrance for those we have los
 t\, a time to honor their lives and contributions\, and to extend our deep
 est condolences to their families\, friends\, and fellow fishermen\; and\n
 WHEREAS\n\, on this day\, Maine organizations that support fishing communi
 ties have come together in a call to action – to renew our shared commit
 ment to improving safety and recovery in the commercial fishing industry\,
  strengthening training\, resources\, equipment\, and awareness to protect
  those who continue to work on the water\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, through rememb
 rance and responsibility\, we honor the past\, safeguard the present\, and
  ensure a more secure future for all Maine fishermen\;\nNOW\, THEREFORE\n\
 , be it resolved that I\, Janet T. Mills\, Governor of the State of Maine\
 , do hereby proclaim July 21\, 2026 as\nMaine Commercial Fishing Remembran
 ce Day\nthroughout the State of Maine\, and I urge all citizens to pause i
 n honor of our fallen fishermen\, to support the commercial fishing commun
 ity\, and to recommit to promoting a culture of safety and wellness on and
  off the water.\nIn testimony whereof\, I have caused the Great Seal of th
 e State to \nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/procla
 mations/2026-07-maine-commercial-fishing-remembrance-day-july-21
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-07-maine-commercial-fishing-remembrance-day-july-21
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:1d12b9acfdbd9071@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260707T151201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Maine Community Health Center Week -
  August 2 through 8
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, for nearly 60 years\, Maine’s community health c
 enters have provided high-quality\, affordable\, comprehensive primary and
  preventive health care in our rural and underserved communities\; and\nWH
 EREAS\n\, as Maine's largest primary care network\, community health cente
 rs are the health care home for over 210\,000 Maine people\; and\nWHEREAS\
 n\, Maine's community health centers are leaders in fighting the chronic d
 isease epidemic by expanding access to primary care\, which keeps people h
 ealthy and out of expensive settings like hospital emergency rooms\; and\n
 WHEREAS\n\, Maine's community health centers develop new approaches to int
 egrating a wide range of services beyond primary care\, including nutritio
 n\, oral health\, vision\, behavioral health\, and pharmacy services\, to 
 provide comprehensive care that allows each patient to thrive\; and\nWHERE
 AS\n\, Maine's community health centers are governed by patient-majority b
 oards\, ensuring patients are engaged in their health care decisions\; and
 \nWHEREAS\n\, Maine's community health centers are locally owned and opera
 ted small businesses that serve as critical economic engines\, helping to 
 power local communities\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Maine's community health center
 s are on the front lines of emerging health care crises\, providing access
  to care for 10 percent of Maine's veterans\, addressing the opioid epidem
 ic\, and responding to public health threats\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Community 
 Health Center Week offers the opportunity to celebrate Maine's community h
 ealth center organizations with more than 100 service delivery sites in al
 l 16 Maine counties\, and we honor their dedicated staff\, board members\,
  patients\, and all those responsible for their continued success and grow
 th since the first community health centers opened their doors over 60 yea
 rs ago\;\nNOW\, THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I\, Janet T. Mills\, Gov
 ernor of the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim the week of August 2-8\, 
 2026\, as\nMaine Community Health Center Week\nand I encourage all residen
 ts to\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamation
 s/2026-07-maine-community-health-center-week-august-2-through-8
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-07-maine-community-health-center-week-august-2-through-8
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:867077455de5ecce@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260707T151201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Wild Blueberry Weekend - August 1 an
 d 2
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, wild blueberries (Vaccinium angustifolium) emerged
  on the rocky\, acidic soils of the barrens of Maine following the retreat
  of the glaciers more than 10\,000 years ago\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, wild blueb
 erries\, which are not planted but grow naturally\, were first managed and
  harvested by the Wabanaki and are now grown by 512 Maine farms on approxi
 mately 40\,000 acres\, within Cumberland\, Franklin\, Hancock\, Lincoln\, 
 Kennebec\, Knox\, Penobscot\, Piscataquis\, Waldo\, and Washington countie
 s\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Maine produces nearly 100 percent of all wild blueber
 ries in the United States\, and they are one of the top three specialty cr
 ops produced in the state\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Maine's wild blueberry grower
 s and businesses are significant contributors to Maine's economy and are v
 ital to Maine's rural communities\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, wild blueberries can 
 be enjoyed fresh during the height of summer in Maine\, while Individual Q
 uick Freezing (IQF) technology allows consumers to buy berries frozen at t
 he peak of freshness all year round\, all over the world\; and\nWHEREAS\n\
 , Maine wild blueberries are one of the world's top 10 superfoods\, a deep
  blue fruit that is rich in antioxidants and health benefits\; and\nWHEREA
 S\n\, wild blueberries are recognized as Maine's official state berry\; an
 d blueberry pie is recognized as the official state dessert\; and\nWHEREAS
 \n\, the Wild Blueberry Commission of Maine is\, in this year of 2026\, or
 ganizing the sixth annual Wild Blueberry Weekend to encourage residents an
 d visitors to visit wild blueberry farms and participating establishments 
 and eat\, drink\, and experience the state's iconic fruit and the landscap
 e where wild blueberries grow\;\nNOW\, THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I
 \, Janet T. Mills\, Governor of the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim th
 e first weekend of August – August 1-2\, 2026 as\nWild Blueberry Weekend
 \nin Maine\, and I encourage all people to recognize the vital contributio
 ns made by the state's wild blueberry growers and businesses to our econom
 y\, and t\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclama
 tions/2026-07-wild-blueberry-weekend-august-1-and-2
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-07-wild-blueberry-weekend-august-1-and-2
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:8eba6cd9503c96c3@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260707T151201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Maine Korean War Veteran Recognition
  Day - July 27
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, on June 27\, 1950\, in response to the communist t
 hreat to South Koreans and their democracy\, President Harry S. Truman com
 mitted the first United States forces to combat in South Korea\, beginning
  the Korean War\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, nearly 1.8 million members of the Unite
 d States Armed Forces served alongside the forces of the Republic of Korea
  and 20 other Allied nations under the United Nations Command to defend fr
 eedom and democracy on the Korean Peninsula\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, the Korean 
 War was one of the bloodiest wars in history\, with 36\,574 American death
 s\, approximately 103\,284 wounded\, and 8\,157 listed as missing-in-actio
 n\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, seventy-three years have passed since the signing of 
 the cease-fire agreement at Panmunjom on July 27\, 1953\, yet the Korean p
 eninsula still technically remains in a state of war\, and the Korean War 
 has become a “Forgotten War” to many Americans\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, the 
 State of Maine recognizes the service and bravery of all Korean War vetera
 ns\, and we remember the 242 Maine people who lost their lives for our nat
 ion during the Korean War\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, in accordance with 1 MRSA § 
 150\, the State of Maine designates July 27th of each year as Maine Korean
  War Veteran Recognition Day\;\nNOW\, THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I\
 , Janet T. Mills\, Governor of the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim Jul
 y 27\, 2026 as\nMaine Korean War Veteran Recognition Day\nthroughout the S
 tate of Maine\, and I urge all citizens to recognize this observance.\nIn 
 testimony whereof\, I have caused the Great Seal of the State to be hereun
 to affixed GIVEN under my hand at Augusta this sixth day of July Two Thous
 and Twenty-Six\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/pro
 clamations/2026-07-maine-korean-war-veteran-recognition-day-july-27
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-07-maine-korean-war-veteran-recognition-day-july-27
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:554d2d45e3e66293@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260707T151201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Wyeth Day - July 12
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, Maine has provided inspiration for much of the bod
 y of work produced by the Wyeth family starting in 1930\, when N.C. Wyeth 
 purchased a summer home in Port Clyde and he built a small studio\; and\nW
 HEREAS\n\, while N.C. Wyeth was best known for his illustrations\, many of
  which were derived from his Maine-based knowledge of coastal and maritime
  life\, he was also an acclaimed painter\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, son of N.C. Wy
 eth and one of the United States’ most celebrated realist painters of th
 e 20th century\, Andrew Wyeth’s detailed paintings depict the land\, sea
 \, and people well known to him\, including the work he is most well-known
  for\, Christina’s World\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Betsy Wyeth\, wife of Andrew
  and mother of Jamie\, helped establish the Wyeth Center at the Farnsworth
  Art Museum and played a key role in founding the Island Institute\, an or
 ganization devoted to sustaining Maine’s coastal and island communities\
 ; and\nWHEREAS\n\, a painter like his father and grandfather before him\, 
 Jamie Wyeth’s paintings of everyday life can be found in the collections
  of the Farnsworth Art Museum\, the National Gallery of Art\, the National
  Portrait Gallery\, the Museum of Modern Art\, the Fine Arts Museum of San
  Francisco\, and many others\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, while members of the Wyeth
  family are known to the world for their generations of fine art\, to many
  Mainers they have been best known as neighbors and friends\; and\nWHEREAS
 \n\, in accordance with 1 MRSA §150-D\, the state of Maine designates Jul
 y 12th\, Andrew Wyeth’s birthday\, as Wyeth Day in recognition of the fa
 mily’s contributions to the State’s artistic and cultural heritage\;\n
 NOW\, THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I\, Janet T. Mills\, Governor of t
 he State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim July 12\, 2026 as\nWyeth Day\nthrou
 ghout the State of Maine\, and I urge all citizens to recognize this obser
 vance.\nIn testimony whereof\, I have caused the Great Seal of the State 
 to be hereunto affixed GIVEN under my hand at Augusta this sixth day of
  July Two Thousand Twe\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_docum
 ents/proclamations/2026-07-wyeth-day-july-12
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-07-wyeth-day-july-12
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:3aa4b32c719badf4@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260704T191745Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] America's Semiquincentennial - July 4
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, on July 4\, 1776\, the Continental Congress adopte
 d the Declaration of Independence\, asserting the United States’ indepen
 dence from Great Britain and setting forth a defining promise of liberty\,
  equality\, and self-government\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, July 4\, 2026\, marks t
 he 250th anniversary of that historic declaration\, known as America’s S
 emiquincentennial\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, the American experiment rests on the 
 enduring principle that power rests with the people – not a king – and
  that liberty is secured through democratic self-government and the rule o
 f law\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, for 250 years\, Americans have sustained that pro
 mise through free and fair elections\, the peaceful transfer of power\, re
 spect for constitutional limits\, and a shared commitment to the instituti
 ons of our democracy\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, while the founding promise of libe
 rty and equality was imperfectly realized at our nation’s birth\, genera
 tions of Maine people and Americans have worked to extend those ideals and
  their benefits more fully to all\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Maine people\, then c
 itizens of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts\, played an early\, consequen
 tial role in the fight for American independence\, including Kittery nativ
 e William Whipple\, the only native Mainer to sign the Declaration of Inde
 pendence\, and the patriots at Machias who captured the British armed cutt
 er Margaretta\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, on June 21\, 1775\, soon after the Battle
  of Bunker Hill\, Penobscot Chief Joseph Orono met with General George Was
 hington at Watertown and agreed that his tribe’s warriors\, as well as o
 thers in the Wabanaki Confederacy\, would join forces with the Continental
  Army to fight a common enemy in the struggle for freedom\; and\nWHEREAS\n
 \, on October 18\, 1775\, British warships shelled and burned Falmouth\, n
 ow Portland\, in retaliation for its resistance to the Crown\, an attack t
 hat strengthened the resolve of Maine people in support of independence\; 
 and\nWHEREAS\n\, the sacrifices of Maine people during the Revolutionary W
 ar helped secur\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/pr
 oclamations/2026-07-americas-semiquincentennial-july-4
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-07-americas-semiquincentennial-july-4
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:a77003411b20d4d5@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] 211 Maine Day - July 7
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, 211 Maine is a Maine-based health and human servic
 es and emergency preparedness and response helpline\, providing free and c
 onfidential referrals to needed resources to Maine people\; and\nWHEREAS\n
 \, 211 Maine provides 24/7 service statewide by people employed in Maine t
 hrough efficient and effective response to the growing complexities and ne
 eds of Maine residents\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, for 20 years\, 211 Maine has wor
 ked diligently to confront and reduce the stigma associated with seeking s
 upport by affirming that doing so reflects personal strength\; and\nWHEREA
 S\n\, since 2006\, 211 Maine specialists have answered more than 1 million
  calls from people across the state looking for needed information from ho
 using support and food resources to substance use and recovery services\; 
 and\nWHEREAS\n\, 211 Maine provides emergency operations support during ti
 mes of natural and other disasters\, including assisting the Maine Emergen
 cy Management Agency field calls from those impacted and collecting data t
 o inform severity and locations of need\, and directing people looking for
  local heating shelters or cooling centers\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, 211 Maine ha
 ndles several specialized services and partnerships\, including providing 
 the Opiate Helpline and the Gambling Helpline\, distributing emergency hea
 ting assistance through the Keep Me Warm fund\, and serving as a resource 
 for mental health services and tax preparation\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, 211 Main
 e stands as a compelling example of how coordinated efforts among governme
 nt\, nonprofit organizations\, and private-sector partners can elevate the
  well-being of Maine's citizens\;\nNOW THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I
 \, Janet T. Mills\, Governor of the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim Ju
 ly 7\, 2026 as\n211 Maine Day\nthroughout the state\, and I urge everyone 
 to utilize and spread awareness of this important resource for Maine peopl
 e.\nthe Great Seal of the State to be hereunto affixed GIVEN under my hand
  at Augusta this twenty fifth day of June Two Thousand Twenty-\nhttp://www
 .maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2026-06-211-mai
 ne-day-july-7
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-06-211-maine-day-july-7
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:4ff19205563342b6@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260623
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Saint Jean-Baptiste Day - June 24
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, Maine enjoys a large\, vibrant Franco-American com
 munity\, largely as a result of French Canadians immigrating to the state 
 between 1840 and 1930\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, at least twenty-five percent of M
 aine citizens claim Franco-American heritage\, and French is the second-mo
 st spoken language in the state\; and\nWHEREAS\,\nthe significant cultural
 \, economic\, and civic contributions made by Franco-Americans have enrich
 ed the culture and lives of Maine people\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Maine benefits
  from a close and prosperous relationship with its Canadian neighbors\, an
 d despite uncertain federal policy Maine will always welcome our Canadian 
 friends to visit our state\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, the feast of Saint Jean the 
 Baptist is an important French cultural observance\, celebrated in America
  as early as 1636\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, in accordance with 1 MRSA § 120\, th
 e State of Maine and its citizens observe June 24th as Saint Jean-Baptiste
  Day\;\nNOW THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I\, Janet T. Mills\, Governo
 r of the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim June 24\, 2026 as\nSaint Jean
 -Baptiste Day\nthroughout the State of Maine\, and I urge all citizens to 
 recognize this observance.\nIn testimony whereof\, I have caused the Great
  Seal of the State to be hereunto affixed GIVEN under my hand at Augusta t
 his seventeenth day of June Two Thousand Twenty-Six\nhttp://www.maine.gov/
 governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2026-06-saint-jean-baptist
 e-day-june-24
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-06-saint-jean-baptiste-day-june-24
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:f73dac11f1838643@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] James Weldon Johnson Day - June 17
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, An Act To Create a James Weldon Johnson Annual Obs
 ervance Day and an Observance Task Force was enacted in Maine on June 20\,
  2021\, to honor the life and perpetuate the legacy of one of our nation
 ’s great Civil Rights leaders\, that of the author\, educator\, journali
 st\, lawyer\, and diplomat James Weldon Johnson\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, this pr
 olific member of the Harlem Renaissance made significant contributions to 
 the preservation and development of African American cultural heritage thr
 ough his poetry\, fiction\, autobiography\, anthologies\, and in collabora
 tion with his brother\, J. Rosamund Johnson\, wrote over 200 songs for Bro
 adway as well as “Lift Every Voice and Sing\,” widely considered to be
  the Black national anthem\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, James Weldon Johnson broke m
 any barriers as the first African American admitted to the Florida Bar\, t
 he first African American Field Director and Executive Secretary of the Na
 tional Association for the Advancement of Colored People\, and the first A
 frican American to serve as U.S. Consul to Venezuela and Nicaragua\; and\n
 WHEREAS\n\, James Weldon Johnson found solace from the endless struggle fo
 r racial justice and his extraordinarily active life among the pines and r
 ocky shores of Maine\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, it was following a tragic accident
  that took place in Wiscasset\, Maine on June 26\, 1938 that this Jacksonv
 ille\, Florida native succumbed to his injuries\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, observi
 ng James Weldon Johnson Day encourages Mainers to learn more about both Ja
 mes Weldon Johnson and our state’s history\, including the many contribu
 tions of African Americans dating back to before statehood\; and\nWHEREAS\
 n\, in accordance with 1 MRSA § 150-Q\, June 17th of each year is designa
 ted as James Weldon Johnson Day in honor of writer and civil rights activi
 st James Weldon Johnson\;\nNOW\, THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I\, Jan
 et T. Mills\, Governor of the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim June 17\
 , 2026 as\nJames Weldon Johnson Day\nin Maine\, and I urge all citizens to
  observe t\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclam
 ations/2026-06-james-weldon-johnson-day-june-17
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-06-james-weldon-johnson-day-june-17
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:84db92b0b9eb5644@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Native American Veterans Day - June 
 21
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, on June 21\, 1775\, soon after the Battle of Bunke
 r Hill in the early stages of the American Revolution\, Penobscot Chief Jo
 seph Orono met with General George Washington at Watertown and agreed that
  his tribe’s warriors\, as well as others in the Wabanaki Confederacy\, 
 would join forces with the Continental Army to fight a common enemy in the
  struggle for freedom\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, members of 33 tribes served as co
 de talkers in World War I and World War II\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, more than 44
 \,000 Native Americans served with distinction between 1941 and 1945\, inc
 luding members of Maine’s Penobscot\, Passamaquoddy\, Maliseet\, and Mi'
 kmaq tribes\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Native American men and women on the home f
 ront were also an integral part of the WWII effort\, with more than 40\,00
 0 leaving their communities to work in ordnance depots\, factories\, and o
 ther war industries\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Native Americans invested more than
  $50 million in war bonds and contributed to the Red Cross and the Army an
 d Navy Relief societies\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Native American women served in
  the Army Nurse Corps during WWI\, and nearly 800 Native American women se
 rved with units such as the Army Corps\, the Army Nurse Corps\, and the WA
 VES throughout the duration of WWII\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Native American men
  and women\, including those from Maine\, have continued to serve in the a
 rmed forces in every war since\, including Korea\, Vietnam\, Desert Storm\
 , Afghanistan\, and Iraq\, and in current operations to enhance the securi
 ty of American partners around the world\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, in accordance 
 with 1 MRSA § 150-C\, the State of Maine and its citizens observe June 21
 st as Native American Veterans Day in remembrance of the courage and dedic
 ated service of Native American members of the United States Armed Forces\
 ;\nNOW\, THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I\, Janet T. Mills\, Governor o
 f the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim June 21st\, 2026 as\nNative Amer
 ican Veterans Day\nthroughout the State of Maine\, and I urge all citizens
  to recognize\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proc
 lamations/2026-06-native-american-veterans-day-june-21
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-06-native-american-veterans-day-june-21
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:01a11fa3709493d6@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Juneteenth - June 19
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, on January 1\, 1863\, President Abraham Lincoln is
 sued the Emancipation Proclamation\, officially ending slavery in the Unit
 ed States\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, the freedom of most slaves depended on the ad
 vancement of the Union Army led by General Gordon Granger\, who enforced t
 he President’s order in Texas on June 19\, 1865\, two and a half years a
 fter the Emancipation Proclamation was signed\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, since 186
 5\, African Americans have celebrated Juneteenth to commemorate the day fr
 eedom was proclaimed to all slaves in the South by General Granger two and
  a half years after the Emancipation Proclamation was signed\; and\nWHEREA
 S\n\, this historic moment would not have been possible without the courag
 e and sacrifice of the nearly 200\,000 former enslaved and free African Am
 ericans who fought for freedom and liberty alongside more than 2 million U
 nion servicemembers\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, Juneteenth commemorates the strengt
 h and determination of African Americans who were first brought to America
 n soil in the hulls of slave ships traveling the trade route known as the 
 “Middle Passage” and celebrates the rich heritage and accomplishments 
 of African-Americans in our country\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, in 2021\, the State
  of Maine and federal government designated June 19 as an official holiday
  in observance of Juneteenth\, and all nonessential state and federal offi
 ces are closed\;\nNOW\, THEREFORE\n\, be it resolved that I\, Janet T. Mil
 ls\, Governor of the State of Maine\, do hereby proclaim June 19\, 2026 as
 \nJuneteenth\nin Maine\, and I urge all citizens to recommit themselves to
  defending the self-evident truth as declared by our founders that all peo
 ple are created equal.\nIn testimony whereof\, I have caused the Great Sea
 l of the State to be hereunto affixed GIVEN under my hand at Augusta this 
 twelfth day of June Two Thousand Twenty-Six\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor
 /mills/official_documents/proclamations/2026-06-juneteenth-june-19
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-06-juneteenth-june-19
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:f9af7e0fafc666e6@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260615
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Executive Order 6: An Order Continui
 ng the Work of Maine’s Elder Justice Coordinating Partnership
DESCRIPTION:FY 25/26\nWHEREAS\n\, a just society exists only when people c
 an age with dignity and respect\, free from abuse\, neglect and exploitati
 on\;\nWHEREAS\n\, an estimated one in 10 older adults in Maine experience 
 abuse each year\;\nWHEREAS\n\, elder abuse is frequently perpetrated by in
 dividuals in positions of trust\, including family members and friends\;\n
 WHEREAS\n\, older adults who experience abuse or mistreatment are three ti
 mes more likely to die within the following decade than adults of the same
  age who are not abused\;\nWHEREAS\n\, research demonstrates that coordina
 ted\, multidisciplinary approaches engaging both the public and private se
 ctors are the most effective means of addressing the pervasive problem of 
 elder abuse\;\nWHEREAS\n\, in 2019\, I established Maine's Elder Justice C
 oordinating Partnership ("Partnership")\, building on Maine's proven succe
 ss with multidisciplinary efforts\, to develop recommendations for prevent
 ing and addressing elder abuse\;\nWHEREAS\n\, the Partnership was charged 
 with developing strategic priorities and recommendations across public and
  private sectors to address and prevent elder abuse\;\nWHEREAS\n\, in 2021
 \, the Partnership issued Maine's first Elder Justice Roadmap\, a comprehe
 nsive and forward-looking set of recommendations to advance elder justice 
 goals statewide\;\nWHEREAS\n\, in 2022\, I established the Cabinet on Agin
 g to ensure that Maine people can age safely\, affordably\, and in ways an
 d settings that best meet their individual needs\, and to coordinate state
  government efforts on a broad range of issues that\, if left unaddressed\
 , contribute to increased risk of elder abuse\;\nWHEREAS\n\, coordination 
 between the Cabinet on Aging and the Partnership has strengthened the Stat
 e's ability to advance elder justice initiatives\;\nWHEREAS\n\, the Partne
 rship has issued an updated Elder Justice Roadmap this month to reflect pr
 ogress made and to identify current and emerging priorities\;\nNOW\, THERE
 FORE\n\, I\, Janet T. Mills\, Governor of the State of Maine\, pursuant to
  Artic\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/executive-o
 rders/2026-06-executive-order-6-order-continuing-work-maines-elder
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/executive-order
 s/2026-06-executive-order-6-order-continuing-work-maines-elder
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:91114a2a500cc5e0@gov-executive-orders.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260612
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Women Veterans Day - June 12
DESCRIPTION:WHEREAS\n\, throughout our nation’s history\, women have ser
 ved honorably and courageously both on and off the battlefield\, though in
 itially in limited and traditional gender roles such as nurses\, cooks\, a
 nd in other administrative support roles\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, during World W
 ar I\, women enlisted in the Navy as Yeoman (F) and the Marine Corps as Re
 servists (F) to serve on the home front as truck drivers\, mechanics\, rad
 io operators\, translators\, and munitions workers\, filling in for men wh
 o were deployed overseas\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, the formation of special units
  in World War II\, such as the Women Accepted for Volunteer Emergency Serv
 ice (WAVES)\, Women’s Army Corps (WACs)\, Coast Guard Women’s Reserve 
 (SPARs)\, Women Airforce Service Pilots (WASPs)\, and the Marine Corps Wom
 en’s Reserve (WRs) allowed women to begin serving in positions previousl
 y reserved for men\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, since all combat positions opened to
  women in 2016\, they now comprise more than 17 percent of the country’s
  military force\, creating more opportunities for recognition and advancem
 ent and allowing for greater equity in military careers and rank\; and\nWH
 EREAS\n\, with more than 10\,000 here in Maine\, women are now the fastest
  growing demographic of veterans\, and the State recognizes their service 
 and sacrifice and we stand by them\, just as they stood by us in their ser
 vice to our state and our nation\; and\nWHEREAS\n\, this year marks the 78
 th anniversary of the Women’s Armed Services Integration Act\, which was
  spearheaded by then Representative Margaret Chase Smith and signed into l
 aw by President Harry S. Truman on June 12\, 1948\, acknowledging the grea
 t contributions made by women in the military and enabling them to serve a
 s regular and permanent members of the United States Armed Forces and Rese
 rves in times of both peace and war and givi\nhttp://www.maine.gov/governo
 r/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2026-06-women-veterans-day-june-1
 2
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/official_documents/proclamations/2
 026-06-women-veterans-day-june-12
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:b40ba67828c9410c@gov-press-releases.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260710T194926Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260710
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Investing in Accessible Housing Acro
 ss Maine
DESCRIPTION:Hello\, this is Governor Janet Mills\, and thank you for liste
 ning.\nEvery family\, I believe\, should be able to make memories in their
  own home\, and yet\, the news is filled every day with stories about the 
 difficulties in renting or buying a house from California to Connecticut. 
 Even if you can find a place that you want\, it may well be beyond your me
 ans. Well\, here in Maine\, we're trying to tackle these problems of acces
 s and affordability\, doing everything we can at the state level\, at leas
 t\, to build up inventory and to preserve homes and apartments that are af
 fordable for families.\nIn 2023\, we released a study that says that Maine
  needs about 80\,000 new homes by 2030 to support our population increase 
 and our future economy. Using that data\, my administration and MaineHousi
 ng set some goals to keep our state on track to meet that target. And last
  month\, we received data showing that we're on track to meet the goal.\nL
 ast year\, Maine communities permitted 7\,500 new housing units—that exc
 eeds our goal by about nine percent. Annual goals will ramp up in the year
 s ahead\, but this good news demonstrates that efforts to make it easier t
 o build homes is working.\nSince I took office\, my administration has aut
 horized more than $350 million to build more homes. That's more than five 
 times what the state of Maine spent on housing production\, in total\, fro
 m 2000 to 2018. We've also worked with the legislature to enact zoning\, l
 and use\, regulatory\, and permitting reforms to allow the private sector 
 to build homes that Maine people can afford.\nWe've expanded tax relief pr
 ograms like the Property Tax Fairness Credit and the Homestead Exemption a
 nd the State Historic Rehabilitation Tax Credit. We created and extended t
 he Affordable Housing Tax Credit\, the largest state investment in housing
  in Maine's history. We created Maine's first-ever long-term funding sourc
 e for affordable housing production with revenue from real estate sales of
  over $1 million\, and that is expected to gener\nhttp://www.maine.gov/gov
 ernor/mills/news/radio_address/investing-accessible-housing-across-maine-2
 026-07-10
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/radio_address/investing-acces
 sible-housing-across-maine-2026-07-10
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:09fd9e6d30786d7b@gov-press-releases.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260704T191745Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260704
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Happy Independence Day Weekend\, Ame
 rica!
DESCRIPTION:Hello\, this is Governor Janet Mills\, and thank you for liste
 ning. And happy Fourth of July.\nThis week\, we celebrate the 250th annive
 rsary of our nation's founding document. That original declaration of prin
 ciples\, that expression of passion that articulates\, among other things\
 , how we Americans are "created equal."\nOf course\, the narrow definition
  of who deserves life\, liberty\, and happiness has been expanded since th
 at time\, following the many struggles for freedom and equality that are a
 lso an important part of our American history. But 250 years ago\, that Co
 mmittee of Five crafted a simple but powerful promise\, endowing us with t
 he "unalienable rights" that belong to every American\, regardless of poli
 tics\, power\, or possessions.\nWhat do you think they envisioned? Would t
 hey ever have dreamed of a continuing nation this far in advance? And the 
 shared values that they embodied in that Declaration that still unite our 
 states and the people of this country two and a half centuries later? Woul
 d they have thought about the people who defied expectations to lead scien
 tific discovery\, and those who took a “giant leap for mankind” on the
  moon? Those who mastered flight in Kitty Hawk\, North Carolina. Those who
  marched for equal rights in Portland\, Maine\, and Montgomery\, Alabama. 
 Those who redefined athletic excellence\, and those who became the King of
  Rock and Roll and the Queen of Soul\, singing anthems that moved generati
 ons to their feet. The people who explored the frontier and rebuilt our ci
 ties after economic crises.\nFamous people and unsung heroes who keep Amer
 ica strong. Schoolteachers like my mother\, potato farmers like my grandfa
 ther\, fishermen like my great-grandfather\, and Americans all over driven
  by a belief—often tested—that our will can overcome any obstacle\, no
  matter how high. That our determination can achieve any cause\, no matter
  how distant. A “self-evident” spirit of discovery\, of bravery\, of c
 ourage\, of kindness that is at the heart of this nation\, at\nhttp://www.
 maine.gov/governor/mills/news/radio_address/happy-independence-day-weekend
 -america-2026-07-03
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/radio_address/happy-independe
 nce-day-weekend-america-2026-07-03
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:9af9aa025e99b45c@gov-press-releases.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260626
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Fighting the Problem of Elder Abuse
DESCRIPTION:Hello\, this is Governor Janet Mills\, and thank you for liste
 ning.\nYou know\, the abuse of vulnerable Maine people\, especially older 
 adults\, is an insidious problem. One in ten older Maine people experience
  abuse or exploitation\, most often committed by someone they actually tru
 st. But only one in 24 cases is actually reported to law enforcement.\nFar
  too often\, older adults are alone and isolated\, and they depend on only
  one or two people\, sometimes family members\, for their well-being\, and
  they're hesitant to ask for help. Eradicating abuse is a shared responsib
 ility\, and it requires state government\, law enforcement\, organizations
 \, and financial professionals to work together to protect older adults.\n
 As District Attorney and later as Attorney General\, I prosecuted many cri
 mes against older Maine people. And in 2014\, I convened a task force to c
 ombat financial exploitation of older people. With that\, we made changes 
 to judicial case management--so prioritizing these cases--changes to staff
 ing\, and changes to specialized training for law enforcement officers\, i
 n order to ferret out abuse and investigate it in a more effective and str
 eamlined fashion.\nIn 2019\, as Governor\, I signed into law "An Act to Pr
 otect Vulnerable Adults from Financial Exploitation\," which requires cert
 ain professionals who suspect financial exploitation to report those conce
 rns to the Office of Securities or Adult Protective Services. In that same
  year\, I signed an executive order to create the Elder Justice Coordinati
 ng Partnership\, and in 2022\, I created the Cabinet on Aging to make sure
  that my administration is doing everything we can to break down silos and
  take every step to protect the dignity\, safety\, and rights of older Mai
 ne people.\nRecently\, I announced the 2026 Maine Elder Justice Roadmap. T
 hat's a report that outlines the progress we've made and which recommends 
 priorities for the next administration through 2028. That progress include
 s investing $4 million in the budget with the su\nhttp://www.maine.gov/gov
 ernor/mills/news/radio_address/fighting-problem-elder-abuse-2026-06-26
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/radio_address/fighting-proble
 m-elder-abuse-2026-06-26
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ad4e7a29b620e4dc@gov-press-releases.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260618
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Millions in Critical Investments are
  Coming to Rural Communities in Maine
DESCRIPTION:Hello\, this is Governor Janet Mills\, and thank you for liste
 ning.\nYou know\, rural Maine is my home. And I know firsthand that our ru
 ral communities have the people\, the work ethic\, and the ideas to build 
 a stronger future. What they haven't always had is the investment that's n
 ecessary to turn that potential into real progress.\nWell\, this week I wa
 s proud to announce that 17 rural communities and organizations across Mai
 ne have been awarded nearly $16 million in federal grants from the Norther
 n Border Regional Commission for some important economic development proje
 cts. The Northern Border Regional Commission\, along with the state of Mai
 ne\, provides targeted federal investment for economic and community devel
 opment projects in counties that are in states along the northern border.\
 nSince the Commission was formed through legislation sponsored by then-Con
 gressman Michael Michaud in 2008\, Maine has received more than $100 milli
 on for hundreds of projects in rural communities. The projects that will r
 eceive funding through these latest awards will enhance economic developme
 nt and build workforce housing\, expand childcare\, and fund infrastructur
 e improvements. For example:\nBrooksville will use its grant to build the 
 town's first all-tide public pier landing and boat ramp at Betsy's Cove.\n
 Tree Street Youth in Lewiston will build a new neighborhood center with ch
 ildcare\, a community meeting space\, and youth workforce training.\nFarmi
 ngton will benefit from a grant to build a multi-use pedestrian and snowmo
 bile bridge over the Sandy River\, extending the Whistle Stop Trail to dow
 ntown.\nAnd the Northern Maine Development Commission will create "Aroosto
 ok Rising\," a two-year project to recruit talented workers.\nI recommende
 d these projects for federal funding after a competitive review conducted 
 by my Department of Economic and Community Development. And recently\, the
  Commission--the Northern Border Regional Commission--also announced award
 s in Maine through its Forest Economy \nhttp://www.maine.gov/governor/mill
 s/news/radio_address/millions-critical-investments-are-coming-rural-commun
 ities-maine-2026-06-18
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/radio_address/millions-critic
 al-investments-are-coming-rural-communities-maine-2026-06-18
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:76891f8fb94adb31@gov-press-releases.maine-government-feeds
DTSTAMP:20260701T202235Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260615
SUMMARY:[Governor / Executive Branch] Protecting Our Homes and Infrastruct
 ure from Extreme Weather
DESCRIPTION:Hello\, this is Governor Janet Mills\, and thank you for liste
 ning.\nWhen I took office nearly eight years ago\, I promised that Maine w
 on't wait to take action to protect our state\, our people\, and our econo
 my from the dangers of extreme weather events caused by pollution and chan
 ges in our environment. And I promised that we would fight to preserve thi
 s special place that we call home for the benefit of our children and gran
 dchildren.\nWe know that the stakes couldn't be higher. Look no further th
 an the devastating storms of just a few years ago that impacted our commun
 ities\, our people\, and our economy. I've made climate action a cornersto
 ne of my administration. We created the Maine Climate Council. We issued a
  groundbreaking climate action plan\, and we dedicated millions of federal
  and state dollars to make that plan a reality.\nIn 2025\, we made the sin
 gle largest investment in storm recovery by any administration in Maine hi
 story\, and we created the State Resilience Office to build better\, stron
 ger public infrastructure in order to withstand future storms. That office
  manages the Community Resilience Partnership\, which includes more than 3
 00 communities that we’re helping. And it has awarded nearly $25 million
  in state and federal funds for local projects to prepare for flooding\, f
 or storm surge\, for rising sea levels\, and other climate events t\nhttp:
 //www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/radio_address/protecting-our-homes-and
 -infrastructure-extreme-weather-2026-06-15
URL:http://www.maine.gov/governor/mills/news/radio_address/protecting-our-
 homes-and-infrastructure-extreme-weather-2026-06-15
CATEGORIES:Governor / Executive Branch
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
END:VEVENT
